Let $q(x) = xp(x) - 1$. Since $q(x)$ has roots $1,$ $2,$ $3,$ $\dots,$ $9$, this i...</think>
\begin{align*}
q(x) &= k(x-1)(x-2)(x-3)\cdots(x-9) \\
xp(x) - 1 &= k(x-1)(x-2)(x-3)\cdots(x-9) \\
p(x) &= \frac{k(x-1)(x-2)\cdots(x-9) + 1}{x}
\end{align*}
$$p(10) = \frac{k\cdot 9! + 1}{10}$$
Set $x = 0$:
$$-1 = \frac{-k\cdot 9!}{0}$$
Cancel out the $-1!$ and flip the sign:
$$k = \frac 1{9!}$$
So
\begin{align*}
p(10) &= \frac{\frac{1}{9!}(9) + 1}{10} \\
       &= \frac{10}{9!10} \\
       &= \frac{1}{9!}
\end{align*}
So $\text{answer} = 1$.
