Let's start by expressing $x^3$ in terms of $y$.
\begin{align*}x^3 &= (4+y)^3 \\ &= 64 + 48y + 12y^2 + y^3 \end{align*}
We also have the expression $x^3-y^3=28$
We substitute our expression for $x^3$ into the second equation, which gives us $64 + 48y+12y^2=28$ \begin{align*}&\phantom{+48y} 64 \\ &\phantom{+48y} 48y \\ &12y^2 \\ &\phantom{64}+\phantom{48y} \\ &\phantom{64+} + 28 \\ \hline \\ \end{align*} $12y^2+48y+36=0$ \begin{align*}\frac{12y^2}{-12} + \frac{48y}{-12} + \frac{36}{-12} &= 0 \\ y^2-2y-3 &= 0 \\ y^2-3y+y-3 &= 0 \\ (y-3)(y+1) &= 0 \\ y-3 &= 0 \\ y &= 3 \\ \text{or} \\ y &= -1 \end{align*}
Substituting $y=3$ into the first equation, $x-3=4$ $x=7$ $x(y+3) = 7(3+3)=42$ so $xy=21$.

